t4422.text: Wow this got away from me. Turns out I had a lot more to say than I first thought.

t4423.text: I did eventually accept myself and stop hiding everything but it wasn’t easy. I don’t regret it though. It’s awesome to finally stop lying to everyone including myself. That’s an understatement but I don’t have the words to describe it.

t4424.text: The realisation that I didn’t have to live this way was freeing but it was also terrifying. How on earth do I stop hiding when it’s all I know how to do? How do I take off the mask when I don’t know where it ends and I begin?

t4425.text: You don’t get any breaks. You always have to be in character. How would you feel? Would you be exhausted from pretending to be someone you aren’t? Well that’s what hiding parts of myself felt like.

t4426.text: I didn’t want to hide anymore. I was so tired of living a half life because that’s what it was. I wasn’t being my true self so I wasn’t really living. Imagine you’re in a stage play and you have to play a character that is very different from yourself.

t4427.text: I spent so long trying to hide all of my disabilities and stay in the closet. I only stopped doing that when I moved out of home and started questioning everything. I realised that my parents and the therapists got it very wrong.

t4428.text: At the time, I thought they were right because they were experts. When you’re a kid, you just trust everything the adults say because you think they know best. So yeah that’s why I took so long to accept myself.

t4429.text: All the therapists they hired said that I had to be indistinguishable from everyone else. I thought that meant I had to hide everything different about me. They said it was for my own good but I know what bullshit that is now.

t4430.text: I knew I wasn’t a girl though. I thought mum just said that to punish me for being rude to Gran. I never told her because I knew I could never tell anyone. If I did, they would know how different I was and that would be bad.

t4431.text: I remember being four years old and sitting on the front step eating chips. Gran came up and stole them and I wasn’t happy about that. I said: “back off! Those are mine Gran.” Mum said something like: “you’re being a rude little girl.”

t4432.text: And yes I had a teacher who actually said that. I lived in a country town so they weren’t always the most open-minded. I always knew I was trans even though I didn’t have the words for it until I was about 18. I just knew there was something different.

t4433.text: I didn’t really know what being bisexual was so that was incredibly confusing. We didn’t get any education about it at school because apparently: “it’s not relevant to the community. We don’t have anyone like that here. That only happens in cities.”

t4434.text: I had a huge crush on someone who appeared in a really popular commercial at the time. I didn’t understand what was going on at the time though. I just remember thinking she had a really nice voice and I was excited every time the commercial came on.
